IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - System driver files modified
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is a change in file attributes Created, LastModified, Permissions, Owner, Group, Size and Contents of .sys files under %WINDIR%\system32\drivers path.
Also the rule provides configuration option to ignore files for monitoring and to select the file attributes to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Default Debugger changed
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule alerts when registry data values for Windows default debugger have changed. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - 'ActiveX Compatibility' registry keys modified (ATT&CK T1112)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule alerts when there is any change in the 'ActiveX Compatibility' registry key set. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - SAM registry keys modified (ATT&CK T1098, T1136)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule alerts when there is a change in registry key entries where SAM Domain Account User's details found. When a user is added to the local system, new registry keys are added under the SAM Domain Account registry path. Generally, these registry entries contain user details like login name, user number, sid name, machine name etc. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - File attributes in the /bin directory modified
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is a change in file attributes in any file under /bin path. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule provides configuration options to select the file attributes that should be monitored and also paths to ignore. It has the potential to monitor a large number of files and also generate large number of events and so exceptions should be configured carefully.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - File attributes in the /etc directory modified
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is a change in attributes of any file under /etc directory. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule provides configuration options to select the file attributes that should be monitored and also paths to ignore. It has the potential to monitor a large number of files and also generate large number of events and so exceptions should be configured carefully.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Windows file protection registry modified (ATT&CK T1112, T1546.008)
IntegrityRule.Description: Windows File Protection (WFP) prevents programs from replacing critical Windows system files. Adversaries may establish persistence by modifying the registry values. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - File attributes in the /lib directory modified
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is a change in attributes of any file under /lib directory. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule provides configuration options to select the file attributes that should be monitored and also paths to ignore. It has the potential to monitor a large number of files and also generate large number of events and so exceptions should be configured carefully.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Network services registries modified (ATT&CK T1547.001, T1574.001)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may achieve persistence by adding a program to a startup folder or may execute their own malicious payloads by hijacking the search order used to load DLLs. This rule monitors such registry keys which can be used for the persistence. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - File attributes in the /sbin directory modified
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is a change in file attributes in any file under /sbin path. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule provides configuration options to select the file attributes that should be monitored and also paths to ignore. It has the potential to monitor a large number of files and also generate large number of events and so exceptions should be configured carefully.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Registry values of event log modified (ATT&CK T1070.001, T1562.002)
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when attributes of registry subkeys and data values changed for settings of Windows Event Viewer. For additional information, see the Details tab.
The rule also provides configuration options to choose registry key and value attributes to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - AutoRun registries modified (ATT&CK T1547.001)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may achieve persistence by adding a program to a startup folder or referencing it with a Registry run key. This rule monitors registry keys and values which can be used to set startup folder items for persistence. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Boot or Logon Autostart Execution registries modified (ATT&CK T1547.004, T1547.014)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may modify Winlogon registries to execute DLLs and/or executables when a user logs in or modify registry key to the Active Setup of the local machine for the persistence. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Microsoft hotfixes registry keys modified (ATT&CK T1112)
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when attributes of registry subkeys changed where Windows Hotfix updates found. It monitors all registry keys where Hotfix entries gets updated in Windows Registry. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule also provides configuration options to choose registry key attributes to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Autostart execution registries modified (ATT&CK T1547.001)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may achieve persistence by adding a program to a startup folder or referencing it with a Registry run key. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Files in appdata startup folder modified (ATT&CK T1547.001)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may achieve persistence by placing a program within a startup folder. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Network configuration files modified
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is any change in file attributes of Network configuration files found under %WINDIR%\inf (e.g., C:\WINDOWS\inf) directory. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule also provides configuration options to exclude files from monitoring and to select the file attributes to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Files in programdata startup folder modified (ATT&CK T1547.001)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may achieve persistence by placing a program within a startup folder. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Directory attributes of /bin modified (ATT&CK T1222.002)
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is any change in attributes of the /bin directory. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule also provides configuration options to select the directory attributes to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Files in start menu directory modified (ATT&CK T1547.001)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may achieve persistence by placing a program within a startup folder. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Directory attributes of /sbin modified (ATT&CK T1222.002)
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is any change in attributes of the /sbin directory. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule also provides configuration options to select the directory attributes to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Attributes of system32 directory modified (ATT&CK T1222)
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when system directory, %WINDIR%\system32 attributes have changed. For additional information, see the Details tab
Note: The rule also provides configuration options to select directory attributes to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Active directory registry keys modified (ATT&CK T1112)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors Active Directory registries keys for the modification. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - DNS Server (ATT&CK T1554, T1584.002)
IntegrityRule.Description: This alert indicates that the files / registry keys / services created by DNS Server were modified. This could indicate that the software was updated or installed / uninstalled. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Active directory files modified (ATT&CK T1552.006)
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule monitors the active directory files for the modification. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: This rule also provides the configuration option to exclude the files to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Application - Mailman
IntegrityRule.Description: This alert indicates that the files / processes created by Mailman were modified. This could indicate that the software was updated or installed / uninstalled. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Installed software attributes modified (ATT&CK T1195.002, T1554)
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is any change in attributes of installed software or program attributes. Also it alerts when a program is installed or uninstalled on windows host. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: Also the rule provides configuration options to ignore monitoring software and to select the InstalledSoftware and RegistryKey attributes to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - 'Hosts' file modified
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is any change in file attributes of Windows 'Hosts' file. For additional information, see the Details tab.
The rule also provides configuration options to select the file attributes to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Software installed, updated or removed
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule alerts when software is installed or uninstalled on the target host. The rule monitors software which is registered using RPM packages on Linux and pkginfo on Solaris. For additional information, see the Details tab

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - File permissions in the /var/log directory modified (ATT&CK T1222.002)
IntegrityRule.Description:
Adversaries may modify permissions to access to log files and with appropriate permissions can delete the activity/attack logs to evade the detection. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: Configuration options are provided to exclude certain files and directories.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Process attributes modified

This rule alerts when there is a change in any process attributes such as CommandLine, Group, Path, Process, User, Parent, Threads.
By default, we do not monitor any process since the change in PID of the process may create many alerts. Hence the rule provides configuration options to include processes to monitor and to select process attributes to monitor.For additional information, see the Details tab.

This rule alerts when there is change in attributes of system files like boot.ini, ntldr, autorun.inf, files with com, exe, bat, ocx, pif, sys extension located under %SystemDrive% (e.g. C:) directory. By default we ignore monitoring pagefile.sys and hiberfil.sys files.
Also the rule provides configuration option to ignore files for monitoring and to select the file attributes to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is change in attributes of system configuration files. For additional information, see the Details tab.

The rule also provides interface to configure installation file path.
Note: onChange feature will not work for the DirectorySet entity set in this rule.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Kernel configuration files modified (ATT&CK T1547.006)

For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Application shimming detected (ATT&CK T1546.011)
IntegrityRule.Description:
The Microsoft Windows Application Compatibility Infrastructure/Framework (Application Shim) was created to allow for backward compatibility of software as the operating system codebase changes over time.
However, certain shims can be abused. Utilizing these shims may allow an adversary to perform several malicious acts such as elevate privileges, install backdoors, disable defenses like Windows Defender, etc. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Software repository modified (ATT&CK T1195.002)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may manipulate the package repository list for the purpose of compromising data or the system. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Task scheduler entries modified (ATT&CK T1053.005)
IntegrityRule.Description: An adversary may use job scheduling to execute programs at system startup or on a scheduled basis for persistence, to conduct execution as part of lateral movement, to gain root privileges, or to run a process under the context of a specific account. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - System wide environment variables and startup scripts modified (ATT&CK T1546.004)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors files that set the environment variables at startup of the Bash shell and contains other scripts that contain application-specific startup files, which are also executed at startup time by the shell. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - AppCert DLL Registry values modified (ATT&CK T1546.009)
IntegrityRule.Description: Dynamic-link libraries (DLLs) that are specified in the AppCertDLLs value in the Registry key HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Control\Session Manager are loaded into every process that calls various ubiquitously used application programming interface (API) functions. This value can be abused to obtain persistence and privilege escalation by causing a malicious DLL to be loaded and run in the context of separate processes on the computer. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - zsh configuration files modified (ATT&CK T1059.004, T1546.004)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may abuse Unix shells to execute various commands or payloads or establish persistence. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Powershell activity detected (ATT&CK T1059.001)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors the execution of the PowerShell, along with PowerShell execution policy registry key, and the WinRM service. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - xinetd configuration files modified
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors the files inside "/etc/xinetd.d/" directory, which contains the configuration files for each service managed by xinetd. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - sudo files modified (ATT&CK T1548.003)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors sudo files. Adversaries may use these files to perform sudo caching and/or use the suoders file to elevate privileges. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - bash command history cleared (ATT&CK T1059.004)
IntegrityRule.Description:
Adversaries can use a variety of methods to clear command history, clearing their tracks. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: By default this rule only monitors root command history. Additional users to monitor can be added under Configuration Options in the Configuration tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Accessibility features registry keys or files modified (ATT&CK T1546.008, T1546.012)
IntegrityRule.Description:
An adversary can modify the way these programs are launched to get a command prompt or backdoor without logging into the system. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: This rule provides configuration option to select files for monitoring.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - csh/tcsh configuration files modified (ATT&CK T1059.004, T1546.004)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may abuse Unix shells to execute various commands or payloads or establish persistence. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - LSA Authentication Packages modified (ATT&CK T1547.002)
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is a change in the data of the Authentication Packages value of the Local Security Authority (LSA) registry key. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: "Authentication Packages" lists the user authentication package that is loaded and called when users attempt to log on to Windows.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Time Provider Registry keys modified (ATT&CK T1547.003)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may abuse this architecture to establish persistence, specifically by registering and enabling a malicious DLL as a time provider. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Service Registry keys modified (ATT&CK T1574.011)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries can change the service binPath/ImagePath to point to a different executable under their control. When the service starts or is restarted, then the adversary-controlled program will execute, allowing the adversary to gain persistence and/or privilege escalation to the account context the service is set to execute under (local/domain account, SYSTEM, LocalService, or NetworkService). For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Removable Device Detected (ATT&CK T1092)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries can perform command and control between compromised hosts on potentially disconnected networks using removable media to transfer commands from system to system. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Root Certificate Registry keys modified (ATT&CK T1553.004)
IntegrityRule.Description: Installation of a root certificate on a compromised system would give an adversary a way to degrade the security of that system. Adversaries have used this technique to avoid security warnings prompting users when compromised systems connect over HTTPS to adversary controlled web servers that spoof legitimate websites in order to collect login credentials. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - OpenSSH registry keys modified (ATT&CK T1021.004, T1112)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors registry keys of OpenSSH server. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - NetSh Helper DLL Registry keys modified (ATT&CK T1546.007)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries can use netsh.exe with helper DLLs to proxy execution of arbitrary code in a persistent manner when netsh.exe is executed automatically with another persistence technique or if other persistent software is present on the system. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - USB storage device detected (ATT&CK T1052.001, T1092)

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Permissions on ssh private host keys modified (ATT&CK T1021.004, T1222.002)

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Possible Ransomware File Rename Activity Over Network Share
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect too many SMB rename operations over the network. The rule will detect the number of SMB file rename operations during the defined number of seconds. After the malicious source is detected the rule will prevent any further SMB file rename and write operation from that source for the defined period of time.
Configuration Note: The rule also has configuration option to exclude the IPs of the client machines doing rename operations.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Possible Ransomware File Rename Activity Over Network Share - Client
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect too many SMB rename operations over the network.The rule will detect the number of SMB file rename operations during the defined number of seconds. After the malicious source is detected the rule will prevent any further SMB file rename and write operation on SMB shares for the defined period of time.
Configuration Note: The rule also has configuration option to exclude the IPs of the SMB Shares where renames operation can be performed by client machine.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Reflected File Download Attack
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Reflected File Download (RFD) is a web attack vector that enables attackers to gain complete control over a user system. In an RFD attack, the user follows a malicious link to a trusted domain resulting in a file download from that domain.
Note: Configuration option is provided to add the executable file extensions to block the RFD attack for the file extensions. Administrators are suggested to add executable file extensions to block the RFD attack according to their Web Application file extension support. The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm their domain are being used to carry out RFD attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Java Runtime Usage In HTTP Request
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects an attempt to use "java.lang.runtime" inside the body of HTTP Request.
While this traffic is not inherently malicious, it can be used to encode malicious code to run on a victim's machine. This DPI rule may generate a lot of events based on the environment.
Configuration Note: Configuration options are provided to set the IP(s) of trusted host(s) to pass traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Restrict File Extensions For Rename Activity Over Network Share
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect SMB rename operations over the network. The rule will detect the file extensions used during the file rename operations and blocks all the rename operations other than the approved list of file extensions. After the suspicious source IP is detected the rule will prevent any further SMB operation from that source for the configured period of time. This rule is in Detect only mode, rule should be configured in Prevent mode to get the rule effectively prevent such source.
Configuration Note: This rule has configuration parameters to provide additional approved list of file extensions. Prevent mode of the DPI rule is not supported if SMB client is Windows 10 and Windows 2012.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Backdoor.Win32.Cobalt.SMHP C&C Traffic Request
PayloadFilter2.Description: This alert is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Microsoft Windows OLE Remote Code Execution Vulnerability
PayloadFilter2.Description: A vulnerability exists in Windows OLE that could allow remote code execution if a user opens a file that contains a specially crafted OLE object. An attacker who successfully exploited this vulnerability could gain the same user rights as the logged-on user.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Microsoft Windows OLE Remote Code Execution Vulnerability - 2
PayloadFilter2.Description: A vulnerability exists in Windows OLE that could allow remote code execution if a user opens a file that contains a specially crafted OLE object. An attacker who successfully exploited this vulnerability could gain the same user rights as the logged-on user.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Unvalidated Redirect And Forward Over HTTP
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects Unvalidated redirect and forward in HTTP traffic via request parameters, query string and headers. Unvalidated redirects and forwards are possible when a web application accepts untrusted input that could cause the web application to redirect the request to a URL contained within untrusted input. By modifying unvalidated URL input to a malicious site, an attacker may successfully launch multiple social engineering attacks.
Note: Administrators are suggested to add trusted domain/IP in the configuration page. The rule will allow all redirects and forwards unless configured.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Web Client Restrict Executable File Downloads
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter blocks EXE file downloads. Administrator can configure this filter and allow certain EXE file downloads.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of WMI Execute Methods - Server
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Windows Management Instrumentation Command-line (WMIC) is a command line tool that executes commands on remote systems and redirects console application output to the local system so that these applications appear to be running locally. This DPI rule identifies the use of WMI Process command through DCERPC request. WMIC is used by malwares and exploits for lateral movement in the network.
Configuration Note: A configuration option is provided to create an approved list of IP addresses that are allowed to execute WMI commands. This rule will detect WMI traffic only when the list of allowed machines has been configured. The rule does not detect traffic in the default configuration.

PayloadFilter2.Name: HTTP Protocol Decoding
PayloadFilter2.Description: Required by all other HTTP DPI rules. This DPI rule decodes the HTTP protocol, restricts URI and query lengths, and validates URI encoding.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Disallow Upload Of A PHP File (ATT&CK T1190)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule to identify the upload of PHP files to a Web Server. These files could be potentially harmful for running applications and could be used for further attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious China Chopper Webshell Communication (ATT&CK T1505.003)
PayloadFilter2.Description: China Chopper Webshell is a malware designed to remotely access Windows or Linux Web servers. The malware has a Web shell command-and-control (CnC) client binary and a text-based Web shell payload (server component). Post infection, the malware enables remote attackers to execute arbitrary code on affected systems. This is a heuristic based rule which detects the HTTP communication of China chopper Webshell.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Web Server Restrict Executable File Uploads (ATT&CK T1190)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter blocks EXE file uploads. Administrator can configure this filter and allow certain EXE file uploads.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Attempt To Brute Force Windows Login Credentials (ATT&CK T1110)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This filter identifies a brute force attempt to determine the Windows password by inspecting the number of failed logins in a time period. An attacker may use automated tools to iterate through all combinations or use a dictionary attack to guess passwords.
Configuration Note: Customers are advised to use the configuration options to tune the rule as per their environment.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Too Many SSL Alert Messages In SSLv3 Over RDP (ATT&CK T1021.001, T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect too many SSL alert messages from a server within a period of time. Such large number of alert messages could be an indication of block-wise chosen-boundary attack, which could allow an attacker to obtain plain-text bytes using SSLv3 protocol.
Configuration Note: Configuration options are provided to customize the alert frequency of the events. Multiple alert messages in SSLv3 protocol can occur legitimately due to server limitations. Hence, every trigger of this rule should be investigated further to confirm an attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: HTTP Web Client Decoding
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a smart filter that decodes the Web Client traffic and is used by other web client filters.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Download Of Executable File Over HTTP (ATT&CK T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment. Files may be copied through FTP, HTTP, SSH etc. This rule monitors Linux and Windows executable files being download over HTTP.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detect UPX Packed Executable Download (ATT&CK T1027.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description: UPX is a universal file compressor and packer for executable files. This filter blocks the download to UPX packed executable files.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft SharePoint GetGroupInfo Request (ATT&CK T1213.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects a UserGroup.GetGroupInfo request to a Microsoft SharePoint instance. The UserGroup.GetGroupInfo method returns information on a specified group from a SharePoint Web site.
Note: This rule might generate a lot of triggers when applied on a Microsoft SharePoint Server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: SMBLoris Denial Of Service Vulnerability
PayloadFilter2.Description:
SMBLoris is a remote and uncredentialed denial of service attack against Microsoft Windows SMB and Unix/Linux Samba servers using memory exhaustion technique. This DPI rule detects an attempt to exploit servers using SMBLoris.
Note: Configuration options are provided to customize the alert frequency of the events.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft SharePoint GetGroupCollectionFromRole Request (ATT&CK T1213.002, T1087)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects a UserGroup.GetGroupCollectionFromRole request to a Microsoft SharePoint instance. The UserGroup.GetGroupCollectionFromRole method returns group information for a SharePoint Web site collection.
Note: This DPI rule might generate a lot of triggers when applied on a Microsoft SharePoint Server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft SharePoint GetGroupCollection Request (ATT&CK T1213.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects a UserGroup.GetGroupCollection request to a Microsoft SharePoint instance. The UserGroup.GetGroupCollection method returns information on a specified group from a SharePoint Web site.
Note: This DPI rule might generate a lot of triggers when applied on a Microsoft SharePoint Server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Potentially Malicious RAT Traffic - VII (ATT&CK T1571)
PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote access tool (or RAT) is a software used to access a remote computer often used for malicious activities. This smart rule identifies suspicious RAT traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Potentially Malicious RAT Traffic - I (ATT&CK T1571)

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft SharePoint GetGroupCollectionFromUser Request (ATT&CK T1213.002, T1087)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects a UserGroup.GetGroupCollectionFromUser request to a Microsoft SharePoint instance. The UserGroup.GetGroupCollectionFromUser method returns information on the collection of groups of which a specified user is a member from a SharePoint Web site.
Note: This DPI rule might generate a lot of triggers when applied on a Microsoft SharePoint Server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft SharePoint GetRoleCollection Request (ATT&CK T1213.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects a UserGroup.GetRoleCollection request to a Microsoft SharePoint instance. The UserGroup.GetRoleCollection method returns information about the role definitions from a SharePoint Web site.
Note: This DPI Rule might generate a lot of triggers when applied on a Microsoft SharePoint Server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Request Smuggling Attack
PayloadFilter2.Description:
HTTP Request Smuggling consists of sending a specially formatted HTTP request that will be parsed in a different way by the proxy system and by the final system, so the attacker could smuggle a request to one system without the other being aware of it. This may lead to bypassing Web Application Firewall protection/Web Proxy and improper cache at Web Cache Servers. Please refer the Details section for more information.
Note: This DPI rule should be preferably applied at in-line proxies. Configuration options are provided to block different attack vectors of HTTP Request Smuggling.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft SharePoint GetGroupCollectionFromWeb Request (ATT&CK T1213.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects a UserGroup.GetGroupCollectionFromWeb request to a Microsoft SharePoint instance. The UserGroup.GetGroupCollectionFromWeb method returns information on the collection of groups from a SharePoint Web site.
Note: This DPI rule might generate a lot of triggers when applied on a Microsoft SharePoint Server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Potentially Malicious RAT Traffic - V (ATT&CK T1571)

This DPI rule detects a UserGroup.GetGroupCollectionFromSite request to a Microsoft SharePoint instance. The UserGroup.GetGroupCollectionFromSite method returns information on the collection of groups from a SharePoint Web site.
Note: This DPI rule might generate a lot of triggers when applied on a Microsoft SharePoint Server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Download of Python Reverse Shell Payload Over HTTP
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic rule to identify the download of python reverse shell payload over HTTP.
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lot of triggers, therefore triggers should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: SMB DLL Injection Exploit Detected (ATT&CK T1055.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule is based on heuristics and will detect dll injection attack is being performed using SMB share. This rule could generate many alerts on some network environment hence each trigger needs further investigation to ensure attack.
Note: This rule only detects traffic and does not block.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Foxit PDF Reader And Editor Multiple Security Vulnerabilities
PayloadFilter2.Description: Foxit PDF Reader and Editor are prone to multiple security vulnerabilities. An attacker can leverage these vulnerabilities to execute code under the context of the current process.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft SharePoint GetUserInfo Request (ATT&CK T1589.003)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This filter detects a UserGroup.GetUserInfo request to a Microsoft Sharepoint instance. The UserGroup.GetUserInfo method returns information on a specified user within a SharePoint deployment.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft SharePoint GetRolesAndPermissionsForSite Request (ATT&CK T1589.003)

Note: This Rule might generate a lot of triggers when filter is applied on a Microsoft SharePoint Server.

PayloadFilter2.Description: Microsoft Windows Support Diagnostic Tool (MSDT) is prone to a Remote Code Execution vulnerability. An attacker who successfully exploits this vulnerability can run arbitrary code with the privileges of the calling application.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Block Administrative Share
PayloadFilter2.Description: Administrative Shares are the default network shares created by all Windows NT-based operating systems. These default shares share every hard drive partition in the system and the windows directory. This filter blocks attempt to access administrative share on a windows machine.

This filter identifies an attempt to reconnaissance information from the Active Directory server over LDAP. This attempt may reveal hidden relationships and identify attack paths within an Active Directory environment that may be used for the lateral movement.
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lots of trigger, therefore trigger should be investigated further to confirm the attack.
Configuration Note: - Configuration options are provided to set the IP(s) of trusted host(s) to pass traffic. - Configuration options are provided to configure the alert frequency. - Configuration options are provided to configure the time for blocking the source of the detected traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Slow HTTP Denial Of Service Attack (ATT&CK T1498.001)

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious User Agent In HTTP Request

PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule detect the upload of a Linux executable file on a web server.

PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to prevent potentially harmful traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Potential Malicious Server Traffic (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to prevent potentially harmful traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule generates alert for traffic matching a known Command and Control due to a malware Trojan.Win64.Anchor.A targeting the Windows platform. Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule generates alert for traffic matching a known Command and Control due to a malware Trojan.Win64.Anchor.A targeting the linux platform. Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Description: Shellcode is a piece of machine code used as the payload in the exploitation of a software vulnerability. This filter will identify common shellcode exploits and some zero day attacks in web client traffic

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Command Injection Attack - 1
PayloadFilter2.Description: Command injection is an attack technique that allows an attacker to inject and execute commands in the vulnerable application. An attacker can exploit command injection vulnerability with a command sequence appended to the appropriate format or escape string to execute arbitrary commands. Successful exploitation results in a system compromise, disclosure or modification of data. This is a heuristic based rule to block command injection attacks. In some network environment further investigation will be required to confirm the attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Trickbot Data Exfiltration - (Application Credentials Grabber)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule generates alert for traffic matching a known Command and Control due to a malware Trickbot. Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified FTP Backdoor.Win32.Qbot.JINX Runtime Detection
PayloadFilter2.Description: Backdoor.Win32.Qbot.JINX is a bot agent that targets the Windows platform. This malware collects a plethora of information from the infected system and sends it to a remote server. Moreover, it steals login credentials for different targeted systems and services. Furthermore, the malware can monitor user's online activities, inject code into target websites, steal banking credentials, download additional plugins, and provide remote access among other nefarious activities. To survive a system reboot, it creates a scheduled task.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Cobalt Strike Malleable C&C Traffic Request (Google Safe Browsing Profile)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This alert is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Description: This alert is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Cobalt Strike Malleable C&C Traffic Request (Pandora POST Profile)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This alert is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Usage Of Shellcode Encoders For Client
PayloadFilter2.Description: Shellcode is a piece of machine code used as the payload in the exploitation of a software vulnerability. To evade detection or due to protocol constraints, shellcode is often encoded using various shellcode encoders. This filter will identify shellcode encoders that are typically used by automated exploitation tools such as Metasploit.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Image Files Over HTTP
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule detects malicious BMP and GIF files. Such files can exploit a weakness in image parsing libraries to execute attack on victim's browser.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Restrict Microsoft .Net Executable File Upload (ATT&CK T1190)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a generic rule to prevent any upload of Microsoft .Net executable over HTTP. Attackers may use malicious Microsoft .NET executable files to cause remote code execution.
Note: This DPI rule should be applied ONLY in server environments where upload of Microsoft .Net executable over HTTP is not allowed.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Upload Of Archive File (ATT&CK T1190)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule to block the upload of certain archive files. The uploaded file could contain malicious code in the form of an exploit, virus, Trojan or malware, which could be used to gain control of the Web server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Disallow Upload Of A JSP File (ATT&CK T1190)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule to identify the upload of JSP files to a Web Server. These files could be potentially harmful for running applications and could be used for further attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Obfuscated JavaScript - 3 (ATT&CK T1203, T1001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule detects suspicious obfuscated JavaScript used by attackers to bypass security and gain unauthorized access to the system. Legitimate web sites could also obfuscate code to reduce security exposure or for intellectual property protection.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Obfuscated JavaScript - 4 (ATT&CK T1203, T1001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule detects suspicious obfuscated JavaScript used by attackers to bypass security and gain unauthorized access to the system.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft Office File With Embedded Executable File
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule is intended to block any Microsoft Office file having OLE compound document with embedded executable file. The detection is for identifying such Microsoft Office files when downloaded over web. Attackers may use crafted Microsoft Office files having embedded executable file to run arbitrary code remotely.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Obfuscated JavaScript (ATT&CK T1203, T1001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects suspicious obfuscated JavaScript used by attackers to bypass security and gain unauthorized access to the system. Legitimate web sites could also obfuscate code to reduce security exposure or for intellectual property protection.
Note: The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Slow HTTP Denial Of Service Attack (ATT&CK T1498.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Slow HTTP Denial-of-Service attacks are caused by exhausting concurrent connection pool and holding connections in open state by sending partial HTTP requests. Tools like Slowhttptest, Slowloris, etc. are used to simulate such DoS attacks. This DPI rule is intended to detect such slow and partial HTTP requests.
Note: By nature of the attack type, this rule may not be able to stop DoS attacks. User configuration options are provided for further customization of the rule.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified DCERPC EfsRpcOpenFileRaw Call Over SMB Protocol (PetitPotam)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This filter detects an EfsRpcOpenFileRaw request using the encrypting file system remote (EFSRPC) protocol.
The EfsRpcOpenFileRaw method is used to open an encrypted object on the server for backup or restore. While not inherently malicious, known exploits of the PetitPotam vulnerability make use of this request.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Obfuscated JavaScript - 1 (ATT&CK T1203, T1001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects suspicious obfuscated JavaScript used by attackers to bypass security and gain unauthorized access to the system. Legitimate web sites could also obfuscate code to reduce security exposure or for intellectual property protection.
Note: The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Download Of DLL File Over WebDAV (ATT&CK T1574.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule is based on heuristics and will detect/prevent DLL file being requested to WebDAV server.
Note: This rule should be applied when DLL files are not expected to be downloaded from the WebDAV shares.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Obfuscated PDF Document (ATT&CK T1027, T1204.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule is intended to block suspicious PDF documents which are obfuscated using lexical conventions.
Note: This rule is always recommended when any version of PDF reader is installed on the computer.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Port Mapper Decoder Passive FTP Server
PayloadFilter2.Description: FTP servers can run in Active and Passive modes. In passive mode, the FTP server opens a dynamic port, sends the FTP client the server's IP address to connect to and the port on which it is listening over the control stream and waits for a connection from the FTP client. This filter decodes the FTP port mapper traffic to find out the dynamic port number over FTP control connection.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious RTF File With Obfuscated PowerShell Execution (ATT&CK T1027, T1204.002, T1059.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule intended to block attempts to load suspicious Microsoft Word RTF files containing PowerShell code, over HTTP traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft Internet Explorer VBScript ShellExecute Command
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects the use of VBscript with ShellExceute command in html files, which may allow remote attacker to gain unauthorized access and execute arbitrary code.
Note: The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm attacks. Customers are advised to configure this rule with allowed IP addresses, from which the VBScript ShellExecute command is allowed to run in Microsoft Internet Explorer.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Usage Of Shellcode In Network Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description: Shellcode is a piece of machine code used as the payload to exploit a software vulnerability. The filter will identify common shellcode exploits and some zero day attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected FTP Server Traffic.
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to detect FTP server traffic. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule which detects if executable file is being uploaded in the Network Share directory through SMB.
Configuration Note: Configuration options are provided to add the IP(s) of trusted host(s) to allow executable file upload on Network Share.

PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule is based on heuristics and will detect if executable file is being uploaded on a SMB share. Hence this rule should only be applied when executable files are not used over the SMB Share.

PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule intends to identify and block the network traffic for Windows Search Protocol (WSP). This works on SMBv1 and SMBv2.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected HTTP Server Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristics based filter to detect HTTP Server traffic on a host. By default, any HTTP Sever traffic identified on TCP ports other than the commonly used 80 and 8080 will trigger this filter. Rogue HTTP servers may indicate policy violations or presence of malicious software on the computer.
This filter will only trigger once per 24 hours for a given host to prevent excessive logging. The monitored ports and frequency of event settings can be modified on the Configuration tab should your environment require different configuration.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of PsExec Command Line Tool (ATT&CK T1569.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
PsExec is a command line tool that execute processes on remote systems and redirect console application output to the local system so that these applications appear to be running locally. This rule identifies the use of PsExec tool through SMB share. PsExec is very powerful tool and used by malware and exploits for lateral movement in the network.
Configuration Note: Administrators are suggested to add trusted IP addresses in the configuration page. The rule will block all PsExec attempts unless configured.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Microsoft OneDrive (ATT&CK T1102.002, T1567.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
OneDrive (previously SkyDrive) is a file hosting service that allows users to sync files and later access them from a web browser. This rule detects Microsoft OneDrive file sharing client traffic based on heuristics. It also provides configuration options to set the event frequency of the rule.
Note: This rule blocks communication of any client with OneDrive storage.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected SMTP Server Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects SMTP server traffic based on heuristics. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: RDP (ATT&CK T1021.001)

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Trojan.MSIL.Sunburst.A Traffic Request

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Backdoor Win32.Beaconsolar.A Runtime Detection
PayloadFilter2.Description: Backdoor.Win32.Beaconsolar.A is a Backdoor that targets the Windows platform. The malware is used in a supply chain attack against high profile entities across multiple industry verticals, whereby the software update from SolarWinds Orion platform were trojanized with this malware. SolarWinds Orion is an IT performance monitoring and management platform. It is reported that this malware is a customized version of CobaltStrike Beacon implant. The malware contacts a remote server for the purpose of identifying itself, and receiving control commands. Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Obfuscated JavaScript For Internet Explorer
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule identifies suspicious Internet Explorer exploits that use obfuscated JavaScript. Attackers tend to obfuscate malicious JavaScript to avoid detection by IPS/IDS product.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious HTTP Traffic (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: HTTP traffic may contain malware traffic (such as worms, viruses, and spyware). This is a heuristics based rule to identify the harmful HTTP request.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Heuristic Detection Of Suspicious Digital Certificate (ATT&CK T1587.003)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule heuristically detects the exchange of Secure Socket Layer (SSL) certificate, which is being used to create reverse HTTPS channel from compromised machine.
Configuration Note: Configuration options are provided to configure valid/legitimate CAs (Certificate Authority) if this rule detects any benign traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: SSH Client (ATT&CK T1021.004)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects SSH client traffic based on heuristics. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: SMTP Client (ATT&CK T1071.003)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects SMTP client traffic based on heuristics. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Windows Live FolderShare (ATT&CK T1102.002, T1567.002)

It also provides configuration options to set the event frequency of the filter. Note: This filter only detects FolderShare traffic and blocks non-encrypted transfers only.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Reflected File Download Attack in URI Query Parameter
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Reflected File Download (RFD) is a web attack vector that enables attackers to gain complete control over a user system. In an RFD attack, the user follows a malicious link to a trusted domain resulting in a file download from that domain.
Note: Configuration option is provided to add the executable file extensions to block the RFD attack for the file extensions. Administrators are suggested to add executable file extensions to block the RFD attack according to their Web Application file extension support. The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm their domain are being used to carry out RFD attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Telnet Client (ATT&CK T1021)

PayloadFilter2.Name: Outlook

PayloadFilter2.Name: FTP Client (ATT&CK T1048.003, T1071.002)

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected SSL/TLS Server Traffic (ATT&CK T1573.002, T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects SSL/TLS server traffic based on heuristics.
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the protocols disallowed, ports monitored and event frequency of the rule.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected HTTP Client Traffic (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristics based filter to detect HTTP Client traffic on a host. For mission critical servers, limited HTTP client traffic means those servers will have less exposure to web related attacks. It also prevents potential backdoor software from contacting external malicious sites.
Note: This filter will only trigger once per 24 hours for a given host to prevent excessive logging. The frequency of event settings can be modified on the Configuration tab should your environment require different configuration. Also rule has option for the IP address exclusion.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected SSH Server Traffic (ATT&CK T1021.004)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This filter detects SSH server traffic based on heuristics.
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter and to allow the client IP address to make SSH connection. Rule will trigger for all SSH clients if not configured with allowed IP address.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected X11 Server Traffic (ATT&CK T1021)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects X11 server traffic based on heuristics. Configuration options are provided to customize ports to inspect or ignore traffic and to set the event frequency of this filter. After appropriate configuration, an event could indicate suspicious activity since X11 traffic over non-standard ports indicates the presence of a backdoor X11 server installation.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected Telnet Server Traffic (ATT&CK T1021)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to detect Telnet server traffic. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Portable Executable File Uploaded On SMB Share (ATT&CK T1021.002, T1204.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule is based on heuristics and will detect if Portable Executable (PE) structure file is being uploaded on a SMB share. Hence this rule should only be applied when PE files such as dll,exe etc. are not used over the SMB Share.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Malicious Java JAR Files
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter blocks malicious java jar files which are known to have been used in the wild.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Java Exploit

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Samba RPC Netlogon NetrServerPasswordSet Request
PayloadFilter2.Description: The Netlogon server implementation in smbd in Samba performs a free operation on an uninitialized stack pointer, which allows remote attackers to execute arbitrary code. This DPI rule detects the rpc netlogon NetServerPasswordSet request.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Exim Sender Email Address
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule is intended to detect a crafted sender's email address. Dovecot when configured with Exim, as a local delivery agent, contains a flaw as the program fails to sanitize input in the 'sender_address' parameter properly. Successful attacks may allow a remote attacker to execute arbitrary commands.
Note: The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Cobalt Strike Default Self-signed SSL/TLS Certificate
PayloadFilter2.Description: This alert is triggered when traffic matching known Cobalt Strike default self-signed SSL/TLS certificate exchange pattern is observed.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Restrict Java Bytecode File (Jar/Class) Download
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule blocks Java Jar files and Class files from being downloaded over HTTP. These files can be used by an attacker to run arbitrary Java code.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Download Of A Suspicious PowerShell Script File Detected

This rule detects a malicious PowerShell script file being download.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Microsoft Word RTF File

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Shellcode In HTML Documents
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a generic DPI rule to block suspicious html files.

PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects RDP server traffic based on heuristics. An event indicates suspicious activity since RDP traffic over non-standard ports indicates the presence of a backdoor RDP server installation.
Configuration Note: Configuration options are provided to customize ports to inspect or ignore traffic and to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Encoded PowerShell Script Execution on Server
PayloadFilter2.Description: Identifies whether a malicious client is attempting to execute an encoded PowerShell script on the server. In certain environments this filter may generate more events, depending on the environment setup and configuration. PayloadFilter2.Description:

PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote access tool (or RAT) is a software used to access a remote computer often used for malicious activities. This smart rule identifies suspicious RAT traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of WMI Execute Methods - Server - 1 (ATT&CK T1047)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Windows Management Instrumentation Command-line (WMIC) is a command line tool that executes commands on remote systems and redirects console application output to the local system so that these applications appear to be running locally. This DPI rule identifies the use of WMI Process command through DCERPC request. WMIC is used by malwares and exploits for lateral movement in the network.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Download Of Executable File Over HTTP
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic rule to identify the download of certain executable files over HTTP. Attackers may use malicious executable files to cause remote code execution.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Spring Boot Actuator Endpoint Access Attempt

This DPI rule identifies the use of WMI Process command through DCERPC request. WMIC is used by malwares and exploits for lateral movement in the network.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified WMI Query Over DCE/RPC Protocol (ATT&CK T1047)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Adversaries may collect sensitive data from the file system or databases using WMI commands.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Download Of Suspicious SCT File Over HTTP
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Microsoft enables scripts that are embedded in an HTML document or in a Windows Scripting Host file to access COM+ objects. An attacker can create COM+ objects in script code stored in an Extensible Markup Language (XML) files, such files are called 'scriptlets' to execute command on the remote host. This is a heuristic based rule which identifies the download of such 'scriptlets' files over HTTP.
Notes: The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Kerberos Null Pointer Dereference Vulnerability
PayloadFilter2.Description: A denial of service vulnerability exists in implementations of Kerberos. The vulnerability is due to improper handling of Ticket-Granting-Ticket renewal requests by a client on a remote, non-Windows realm in a mixed-mode Kerberos implementation. An attacker who successfully exploited this vulnerability could cause the affected Windows domain controller to stop responding. Note: This filter should be applied on Windows Domain Controllers using Kerberos authentication.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Command Injection Attack
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Command injection is an attack technique that allows an attacker to inject and execute commands in the vulnerable application. An attacker can exploit command injection vulnerability with a command sequence appended to the appropriate format or escape string to execute arbitrary commands. Successful exploitation results in a system compromise, disclosure or modification of data. This is a heuristic based rule to block command injection attacks. In some network environment further investigation will be required to confirm the attack.
Note: Configuration options are provided to configure the parameter names where commands are allowed.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Remote Service Creation Over DCE/RPC Protocol (ATT&CK T1543.003)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule detects remote service creation over DCE/RPC protocol. Adversaries may install a new service that can be configured to execute at startup by using utilities to interact with services or by directly modifying the registry. These services can be leverage to escalate privileges from administrator to SYSTEM.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Possible Ransomware File Extension Create Activity Over Network Share - Client (ATT&CK T1486, T1080)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect SMB create operations over the network. The rule will detect the file extensions used during the file create operations. After the malicious source is detected the rule will prevent any further SMB file create, write and delete operation from that source for the defined period of time.
Note: This rule has configuration parameters to monitor and to exclude the file extensions.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Jar File
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a generic rule to prevent the download of malicious Jar files over the web. Attackers may use crafted Jar files to cause remote code execution.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Potentially Malicious RAT Traffic - IV (ATT&CK T1571)
PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote access tool (or RAT) is a software used to access a remote computer often used for malicious activities. This smart rule identifies suspicious RAT traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Trojan-Downloader.Shell.Lightbot.A C&C Traffic Request
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule generates alert for traffic matching a known Command and Control due to a malware Trojan-Downloader.Shell.Lightbot.A. Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Disallow Download Of Restricted File Formats (ATT&CK T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment. Files may be copied through FTP, HTTP, SSH etc. This rule detects files being download over HTTP.
Note: With default configuration rule monitors ".tmp, .dat, .sh, .ps1" files from being download over HTTP. Also configuration option is provided to add more file extensions to monitor.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Executable File Download On Network Share Detected
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule is based on heuristics and will detect executable file being accessed over SMB share. Hence this rule should only be applied when executable files are not used over the SMB Share.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Remote Service Creation Over DCE/RPC Protocol (Invoke-SMBexec Tool)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule detects remote service creation over DCE/RPC protocol. Attackers may install a new service that can be configured to execute at startup by using utilities to interact with services or by directly modifying the registry. These services can be leverage to escalate privileges from administrator to SYSTEM.
Note: This rule when applied might generate number of events depending upon the environment. Also, triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm the attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft BAT And CMD Files Over WebDAV
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule to detect .bat and .cmd files being accessed over WebDAV. A remote code execution vulnerability exists in the way that Microsoft Windows processes .bat and .cmd files that are run from an external network. An attacker who successfully exploited this vulnerability could take complete control of an affected system.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Image With Embedded PHP Code
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule is a heuristic based rule to detect malicious php code embedded within gif, jpg and png image files. An attacker may use maliciously crafted image file to do remote code execution and take control of the victim's host machine.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Microsoft Project MPT File Parsing Out-Of-Bounds Read Vulnerability (ZDI-CAN-14518)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This vulnerability allows remote attackers to disclose sensitive information on affected installations of Microsoft Project. The specific flaw exists within the parsing of MPT files. The issue results from the lack of proper validation of user-supplied data, which can result in a read past the end of an allocated buffer. An attacker can leverage this vulnerability to disclose information in the context of the current process.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Windows Port Mapper Decoder
PayloadFilter2.Description: Microsoft Remote Procedure Call (RPC) is an interprocess communication (IPC) mechanism that enables data exchange and invocation of functionality residing in a different process. A client will call the endpoint mapper (EPM) at the server to ask for a "well known" service. The server will answer the client at which port this service is available. This rule decodes the port shared by the Server using DCE/RPC Endpoint Mapper (EPM) Protocol, and helps other rules for monitoring traffic on the dynamically opened port.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Cobalt Strike Malleable C&C Traffic Response (YouTube Profile)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Alert for this DPI Filter is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Cobalt Strike Beacon C&C HTTP communications could be customized with what's known as malleable C2 profiles. Those profiles are meant to mimic legitimate services requests, such as, Amazon, Google and Office 365, among others, for the purpose of hiding malicious traffic. Moreover, they could be also used for emulating a known malware C&C traffic.
Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Cobalt Strike Malleable C&C Traffic Response (Office 365 Calendar Profile)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Alert for this DPI Filter is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed.
