Moreover, they could be also used for emulating a known malware C&C traffic.
Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Reverse Shell Communication Over HTTPS - 3 (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule heuristically detects the initial communication between the compromised machine and C&C server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Reverse Shell Communication Over HTTPS - 2 (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule heuristically detects the initial communication between the compromised machine and C&C server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: SMTP Decoding
PayloadFilter2.Description: The filter decodes the SMTP Protocol and will be used by other SMTP filters. It should be enabled on all the SMTP filters. The filter will have to be active on application type listening on port 25.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Microsoft DLL File Over Network Share
PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote code execution vulnerability exists in the way that the Microsoft Windows handles the loading of DLL files. An attacker who successfully exploited this vulnerability could take complete control of an affected system. This rule is based on heuristics and will only detect DLL file being accessed over SMB share. Hence this rule should be applied when DLL files are not used over the network.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Out-Of-Sync RPCSEC_GSS_CONTINUE_INIT RPC Message
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects RPCSEC_GSS_CONTINUE_INIT RPC message, if it comes before RPCSEC_GSS_INIT RPC message, which is a suspicious condition.
Note: Alerts from this rule should be investigated further to confirm the attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Disallow Packed Executable Download Over HTTP
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule detects the transfer of executables ,over HTTP, which are packed with known versions of packers commonly used for malicious executables.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Usage Of Shellcode In Microsoft Office Files
PayloadFilter2.Description: Shellcode is a piece of machine code used as the payload in the exploitation of a software vulnerability which attempts to execute code without the affected user's consent. This is a heuristic based rule to identify common shellcode exploits in office files.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Windows Group Policy Files Downloaded From Untrusted Sources
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule identify domain-joined computers downloading Group Policy files from untrusted sources.
This rule is intended to protect against attacks where the client machine is being redirected to execute a malicious Group Policy file hosted in malicious sever. By default, this rule will not block any machine or Domain Controller server. Configuration options are provided to add the trusted Domain Controller IPs.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Java Code Download Attempt Over LDAP
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects java code download attempt over LDAP request.
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lot of triggers, therefore triggers should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Restrict Attempt To Enumerate Microsoft SharePoint For User Accounts (ATT&CK T1087.003, T1087.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This filter identifies an attempt to enumerate user account information on a Microsoft SharePoint Server. This filter detects a UserGroup.GetUserCollectionFromSite or UserGroup.GetUserCollectionFromWeb request method to a Microsoft Sharepoint instance. The UserGroup.GetUserCollectionFromSite or UserGroup.GetUserCollectionFromWeb method returns user information from a SharePoint Site Collection or Website.
Note: This Rule might generate a lot of triggers when filter is applied on a Microsoft SharePoint Server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Unsecured Credentials - Cloud Instance Metadata API (ATT&CK T1552.005)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule detects attempts to access the Cloud Instance Metadata API and collect credentials and other sensitive data. It currently protects workloads on the following Cloud Service Providers: Amazon Web Services, Google Cloud Platform and Microsoft Azure.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of PAExec Command Line Tool (ATT&CK T1569.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
PAExec is a command line tool that execute processes on remote systems and redirect console application output to the local system so that these applications appear to be running locally. This rule identifies the use of PAExec tool through SMB share. PAExec is very powerful tool and used by malware and exploits for lateral movement in the network.
Configuration Note: Administrators are suggested to add trusted IP addresses in the configuration page. The rule will block all PAExec attempts unless configured.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Image File With Embedded PHP Code
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule is a heuristic based rule to detect malicious php code embedded within gif, jpg and png image files. An attacker may use maliciously crafted image file to do remote code execution and take control of the victim's host machine.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Downloading Of PowerShell Scripts Through SMB Share (ATT&CK T1059.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: PowerShell may also be used to download and run PowerShell scripts from the Internet, which can be executed from disk or in memory without touching disk. Adversaries may use PowerShell to execute malicious PowerShell scripts that may cause Damage of the system.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Backdoor.MSIL.Supernova.A Traffic Request
PayloadFilter2.Description: The alerts from this DPI rule is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified NTLMv1 Authentication Attempt Over SMB
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule detects NT LAN Manager (NTLM) Authentication Protocol which is used in Microsoft Windows workgroups for authentication between clients and servers.
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this rule. By default, this rule blocks all NTLMv1 traffic. Administrators are advised to configure this rule with IP(s) of trusted host(s) to pass traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Trojan.MSIL.Sunburst.A Traffic Request - 1
PayloadFilter2.Description: The alerts from this DPI rule is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious JavaScript Encoded Shellcode
PayloadFilter2.Description: Shellcode is a piece of machine code used as the payload to exploit a software vulnerability. This filter detects suspicious web browser exploits and some zero day attacks that use JavaScript to encode shellcode.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified BADRABBIT Ransomware Propagation Over SMB
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule blocks lateral movement of BADRABBIT ransomware over SMB.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP TrojanDownloader.Win64.BazarLoader Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This alert is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Trojan.Win64.BazarTrickbot.A is a Trojan that targets Windows platform. It has been reported that this malware is used as a payload by BazarBackdoor, a stealthy covert malware, for high-value targets. The malware is capable to execute files, scripts, and modules. It is also capable to kill processes and remove itself from the infected system.
Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Microsoft Windows OLE Remote Code Execution Vulnerability Over SMB
PayloadFilter2.Description: A vulnerability exists in Windows OLE that could allow remote code execution if a user opens a file that contains a specially crafted OLE object over SMB. An attacker who successfully exploited this vulnerability could gain the same user rights as the logged-on user.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Microsoft Windows OLE Remote Code Execution Vulnerability - 3
PayloadFilter2.Description: A vulnerability exists in Windows OLE that could allow remote code execution if a user opens a file that contains a specially crafted OLE object. An attacker who successfully exploited this vulnerability could gain the same user rights as the logged-on user.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified TCP Meterpreter Payload
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Meterpreter is an advanced and extensible Backdoor that is stealthy and highly resilient to detection. Additionally, it is used in post-exploitation attacks as a means to establish a foothold on an infected network. Moreover, it is generated by Metasploit, the penetration testing framework. Note that Meterpreter is also known as Beacon with other adversary simulations and red team operations frameworks such as CobaltStrike and Armitage.
Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Trojan.Win64.BazarTrickbot Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This alert is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Trojan.Win64.BazarTrickbot.A is a Trojan that targets Windows platform. It has been reported that this malware is used as a payload by BazarBackdoor, a stealthy covert malware, for high-value targets. The malware is capable to execute files, scripts, and modules. It is also capable to kill processes and remove itself from the infected system.
Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified DNS Trojan.Win32.Trickbot.Dns Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This alert is triggered when traffic matching a known Trickbot check-in request over DNS is observed. Trickbot is a banking stealer Trojan that targets the Windows platform. The malware functionality is modular, and each module is responsible for different functionality of the malware. This variant of Trickbot known as "Anchor DNS" is responsible for communicating with the C&C server over the DNS protocol. It contacts the server for the purpose of identifying itself, sending system specific information, and exfiltrating/receiving data.
Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Backdoor.Shell.Powertrick.A Runtime Detection
PayloadFilter2.Description: Backdoor.Shell.Powertrick.A is a Backdoor that targets Windows platform. It is reported that this malware is used by organized cyber-crime group to conduct fileless stealthy attack on high-value targets. The malware is capable to execute command on the infected system and send the result back to the server. It is also reported that Powertrick is used to download Trickbot on the infected system.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified TLS Cobalt Strike Beacon (Certificate)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Beacon is an advanced and extensible Backdoor that is stealthy and highly resilient to detection. It is used in post-exploitation attacks as a means to establish a foothold on an infected network.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Microsoft Windows OLE Remote Code Execution Vulnerability Over WebDAV
PayloadFilter2.Description: A vulnerability exists in Windows OLE that could allow remote code execution if a user opens a file that contains a specially crafted OLE object over WebDAV. An attacker who successfully exploited this vulnerability could gain the same user rights as the logged-on user.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Trickbot Data Exfiltration (Network Module)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Trickbot is a banking stealer Trojan that targets the Windows platform. The malware communicates over SSL/TLS channel, however, one of its module, and in particular, the network module, communicates over HTTP. This module is responsible for collecting plethora of system information and sending it to a remote server. Collected information includes, list of all running processes, OS, user and domain specific information, among others.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Malware Activity
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule is intended to detect the "Operation DeputyDog" campaign leveraging the Internet Explorer zero-day CVE-2013-3893.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Trickbot Data Exfiltration (Card Payment)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Trickbot is a banking stealer Trojan that targets the Windows platform. The malware communicates over SSL/TLS channel, however, some of its modules communicate over HTTP. This filter covers the module that steals payment card data and sends it to a remote C&C server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Cobalt Strike Malleable C&C Traffic Request (Office 365 Calendar Profile)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Alert for this DPI Filter is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Cobalt Strike Beacon C&C HTTP communications could be customized with what's known as malleable C2 profiles. Those profiles are meant to mimic legitimate services requests, such as, Amazon, Google and Office 365, among others, for the purpose of hiding malicious traffic. Moreover, they could be also used for emulating a known malware C&C traffic.
Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Cobalt Strike Malleable C&C Traffic Request (Amazon Profile)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Alert for this DPI Filter is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Cobalt Strike Beacon C&C HTTP communications could be customized with what's known as malleable C2 profiles. Those profiles are meant to mimic legitimate services requests, such as, Amazon, Google and Office 365, among others, for the purpose of hiding malicious traffic. Moreover, they could be also used for emulating a known malware C&C traffic.
Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified User Creation Attempt In GitStack
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects an attempt to create a user in GitStack software.
Configuration Note: Configuration options are provided to set the IP(s) of trusted host(s) to pass traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft SharePoint GetPermissionCollection Request (ATT&CK T1069, T1213.002, T1589.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects a Permissions.GetPermissionCollection request to Microsoft SharePoint. The Permissions.GetPermissionCollection method returns the collection of permissions for a SharePoint site or list.
Note: This rule might generate a lot of triggers when applied on a Microsoft SharePoint Server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Possible Ransomware File Extension Create Activity Over Network Share (ATT&CK T1486, T1080)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect SMB create operations over the network. The rule will detect the file extensions used during the file create operations. After the malicious source is detected the rule will prevent any further SMB file create, write and delete operation from that source for the defined period of time.
Configuration Note: This rule has configuration parameters to monitor and to exclude the file extensions.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Windows Client Port Mapper Decoder
PayloadFilter2.Description: Remote Procedure Call (RPC) is an interprocess communication (IPC) mechanism that enables data exchange and invocation of functionality residing in a different process. A client will call the endpoint mapper (EPM) at the server to ask for a "well known" service. The server will answer the client at which port this service is available. This rule decodes the port shared by the Server using DCE/RPC Endpoint Mapper (EPM) Protocol, and help other rules for monitoring traffic on the dynamically opened port.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Download Of XML File Over HTTP
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule prevents the download of large XML file over HTTP. Attackers may use crafted XML files to cause remote code execution. It may corrupt memory in such a way that an attacker could execute arbitrary code in the context of the logged-on user.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Bash ShellShock Attack
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Bash is prone to a remote code execution vulnerability when it incorrectly processes trailing strings after certain malformed function definitions in the values of environment variables, which allows remote attackers to write to files or possibly have unknown other impact via a crafted request. This is a heuristic based rule to detect such attacks.
Note: In some network environment this rule could generate many alerts, hence every trigger should be investigated further to confirm the attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected SMB Request
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic rule intended to detect SMB version 1,2 and 3 requests. By default rule only monitors all SMB versions.
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this rule and the SMB versions to monitor.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Possible Ransomware File Extension Rename Activity Over Network Share
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect SMB rename operations over the network. The rule will detect the file extensions used during the file rename operations. After the malicious source is detected the rule will prevent any further SMB file rename and write operation from that source for the defined period of time.
Configuration Note: This rule has configuration parameters to monitor and to exclude the file extensions and IPs of the client machines doing rename operations.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Possible Ransomware File Extension Rename Activity Over Network Share - Client
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect SMB rename operations over the network. The rule will detect the file extensions used during the file rename operations. After the malicious source is detected the rule will prevent any further SMB file rename and write operation to the network share for the defined period of time.
Configuration Note: This rule has configuration parameters to monitor and to exclude the file extensions and the IPs of the SMB Shares where renames operation can be performed by client machine.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Kerberos Authentication with Spoofed Certificate
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This filter detects an attempt to use a spoofed certificate to authenticate to a server using Kerberos. The spoofed certificate can be obtained by exploiting a vulnerability in the Windows Active Directory Certificate Services (AD CS) Server.
Configuration Note: Configuration option is provided to add a hostname of Domain Controller, to protect its critical resources from being retrieved by an attacker, with the help of spoofed certificate.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Usage Of Shellcode Encoders
PayloadFilter2.Description: Shellcode is a piece of machine code used as the payload in the exploitation of a software vulnerability. To evade detection or due to protocol constraints, shellcode is often encoded using various shellcode encoders. This filter will identify shellcode encoders that are typically used by automated exploitation tools such as Metasploit and Canvas.

PayloadFilter2.Name: SSL/TLS Client (ATT&CK T1573.002, T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects SSL/TLS client traffic based on heuristics.
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the protocols disallowed, ports monitored and event frequency of the rule.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft Office File With Embedded TIFF File
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule is intended to block any Microsoft Office file embedded with TIFF over web. Attackers may use crafted Microsoft Office files having embedded TIFF file to run arbitrary code remotely.
Note: TIFF files can be embedded in Microsoft Office files in multiple ways. This rule detects TIFF files embedded in Microsoft Office in certain known ways. And the rule does not detect Microsoft Office Open XML format (docx, pptx, etc.) files.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected Web Client Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristics based filter to detect HTTP Client traffic by using Wget and Curl user agent. For mission critical servers, limited HTTP client traffic means those servers will have less exposure to web related attacks. It also prevents potential backdoor software from contacting external malicious sites.
This filter will be triggered once per minute for a given host. The frequency of event settings can be modified on the Configuration tab should your environment require different configuration.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified BumbleBee Webshell Traffic Over HTTP
PayloadFilter2.Description: This alert is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

ConnectionType.Name: SAP NetWeaver Java Application Server
ConnectionType.Description:
These ports are used for communication with the NetWeaver AS Java as part of SAP NetWeaver Application Server. Ports are : TCP\50000 - 50001.
Reference : https://help.sap.com/viewer/ports Search Java on this page and it shows.

ConnectionType.Name: Web Server Common
ConnectionType.Description: Smart and vulnerability facing filters common to all web servers.

ConnectionType.Name: Web Server SharePoint
ConnectionType.Description: Using SharePoint people can set up Web sites to share information with others, manage documents from start to finish, and publish reports to help everyone make better decisions.

ConnectionType.Name: Windows Remote Management Client
ConnectionType.Description: Identify the usage of WinRM on client machine to detect the originating machine in case of using WinRM for lateral movement.

ConnectionType.Name: DCERPC Services
ConnectionType.Description: Remote procedure call (RPC) is a protocol that is used by the Windows and Linux (Samba) operating system. RPC provides an inter-process communication mechanism that allows a program that is running on one computer to seamlessly access services on another computer. The protocol itself is derived from the Open Software Foundation (OSF) RPC protocol.
